#### Chairmen of the Central Executive Committee

Following the initial revolutionary period and the adoption of the 1921 Constitution, the Central Executive Committee became the supreme legislative authority, presided over by its chairmen.

*   Mukhtar Gajiyev (1921–1922)
*   Samed Aliyev (1922–1929)
*   [Gazanfar Musabekov](/Gazanfar_Musabekov) (1929–1931)
*   [Sultan Medjid Efendiev](/Sultan_Medjid_Efendiev) (1932–1937)
*   [Mir Bashir Gasimov](/Mir_Bashir_Gasimov) (1937–1938)

#### Chairperson of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet

*Main article: [Chairperson of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic](/Chairperson_of_the_Presidium_of_the_Supreme_Soviet_of_the_Azerbaijan_Soviet_Socialist_Republic)*

With the 1937 Constitution, the legislative functions were transferred to the Supreme Soviet, and its Presidium was headed by a Chairperson, acting as the ceremonial head of state.

#### President of the Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic

In the final, tumultuous years before independence, a new executive office was introduced, reflecting a shift towards a more presidential system within the Soviet framework.

*   [Ayaz Mutallibov](/Ayaz_Mutallibov) (1990–1991)

### Military

The military posture of the Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic, as with all other union republics, was inextricably linked to the broader military structure of the former Soviet Union. In the period immediately preceding its declaration of independence, Azerbaijan served as a significant staging ground for Soviet military might. The republic hosted an imposing force of over 60,000 Soviet military personnel, strategically deployed across the country in various units belonging to the Ground Forces, Air Forces, Air Defense Forces, and the Soviet Navy.

The principal combat formation of the Ground Forces stationed in Azerbaijan was the formidable [4th Army](/4th_Army_(Soviet_Union)). Its headquarters, along with a multitude of essential support units, were situated in the strategically vital city of [Baku](/Baku). Beyond these central command structures, the Fourth Army's core combat elements comprised several [motorized rifle divisions](/Mechanized_infantry) (MRD), including the 23rd MRD based in [Ganja](/Ganja,_Azerbaijan), the 295th MRD in [Lenkaran](/Lankaran), the 60th MRD in Baku itself, and the 75th MRD stationed in the [Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic](/Nakhchivan_Autonomous_Republic). These divisions were augmented by independent [surface-to-air missile](/Surface-to-air_missile) (SAM), artillery, and [SCUD](/SCUD) brigades, providing a layered defense and offensive capability. Furthermore, the Ganja Helicopter Assault Regiment, equipped with robust [Mi-24 Hinds](/Mil_Mi-24) and versatile [Mi-8 Hips](/Mil_Mi-8), represented a crucial aerial component for rapid deployment and close air support.

For the training of its ground forces, Azerbaijan hosted a singular, yet vital, institution: the [Baku Higher Combined Arms Command School](/Baku_Higher_Combined_Arms_Command_School), which served as a crucible for future Soviet military officers. It is worth noting that military conscription within the Azerbaijan SSR was not an immediate imposition upon the establishment of Soviet control. Rather, it was introduced only after the consolidation of Soviet authority, and even then, the initial numbers of individuals called up for service were relatively minimal, perhaps reflecting a cautious approach to integrating the local populace into the broader Soviet military apparatus.